imary function of pro-inflammatory cytokines?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibit prostaglandin synthesis","Suppress neutrophil activation","Decrease vascular permeability","Stimulate acute phase protein production","Reduce hypothalamic temperature set point"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulate acute phase protein production\u003C/strong\u003E is a key function of pro-inflammatory cytokines, particularly interleukin-1 and tumour necrosis factor-alpha. These cytokines act on hepatocytes to increase synthesis of acute phase proteins such as C-reactive protein, which contribute to host defence.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppress neutrophil activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Pro-inflammatory cytokines actually promote neutrophil activation and recruitment\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecrease vascular permeability\u003C/strong\u003E - Pro-inflammatory cytokines increase vascular permeability to facilitate immune cell migration\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibit prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Pro-inflammatory cytokines stimulate prostaglandin production via cyclooxygenase-2 induction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduce hypothalamic temperature set point\u003C/strong\u003E - Pro-inflammatory cytokines raise the hypothalamic temperature set point to induce fever\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPro-inflammatory cytokines orchestrate multiple aspects of the acute inflammatory response including fever, increased vascular permeability, and production of acute phase proteins to combat infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Interleukin-1 and tumour necrosis factor-alpha are key pro-inflammatory cytokines that initiate the acute phase response.","Pro-inflammatory cytokines induce fever by acting on the hypothalamus to raise the temperature set point.","Pro-inflammatory cytokines stimulate the liver to produce acute phase proteins like C-reactive protein."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62907"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18761"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62907"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T21:40:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T21:40:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11493"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77400"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":